This is a Carriage designed to glide smoothly on 25mm 80-20 Aluminum extrusion, which is commonly used to build 3D Printers. The model uses Openbuilds Carriage wheels and 10mm spacers, but included are all of the files needed to make the carriage. If you would like optimal results though i would definitely recommend using the Openbuilds wheels instead of printing them. The carriages also have set screw adjustment to tighten the wheel against the extrusion, this is essential for tuning. The part was originally designed to work for my Delta 3D Printer as its main source of linear movement, and has worked flawlessly for every part so far:) Links are below to the whole printer. Here is a short teaser video of the Delta 3D Printer- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EX2o5emcHi4 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1266969 UPDATE 1-23-17 --------------------------------- Hello everyone, Over the past many months and thousands of hours of design time I am nearly ready to release the final version of my consumer version of the Dimension 3 MultiMachine Delta 3D Printer. Check it out at http://www.Dimension3fab.com

Printer:

Custom Delta 3D Printer

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 or .2

Infill:

40%

Notes: Make sure it is well adhered to the plate:)

Cleaning up the prints After the prints are done simply remove all supports and pop it together. Gathering Materials To build the carriages you will need a few bits of hardware.
  • 3 50mm m5 bolts with matching Nyloc nuts
  • 6 Printed 10mm Spacers
  • 3 Openbuilds Solid V Wheel Kit (http://openbuildspartstore.com/solid-v-wheel-kit/)
  • 2 25mm m3 Bolts with matching nut for delta arm connection
  • 2 1" long 6/32" screw (for wheel tightening)
    • Assembly First you are going to add the set screw in the side of the plates for tightening the wheel. Then slide one of the 50mm m5 bolts and slide it through the back plate. After that slide on a 10mil spacer then an openbuilds wheel, then another 10mil spacer. Finally slide on the front plate and bolt it all together. Do the same thing for the other two wheels. Mounting to the extrusion After two wheels are mounted then connect it to the printer by attaching the third wheel and spacers. Once it is bolted together and sitting on the extrusion you can tighten the set screws to bring the third wheel closer to the extrusion and thus tightening up the whole system. Delta Setup Once they are mounted you can use the 2 25mm m3 screws to mount the arms of the delta printer to the carriage plates. There are also two slots perfectly fitted for a G2 2mm pitch 6mm wide belt, which is pictured above. I used Traxxas ball joints for my arms, so that is what i designed this to use, but you can adapt it to work with lots of different arm designs.

Hi ! Got a question here , due to I am new to 3d , may I know what is the print material that you use ? ABS or PLA ?
Thanks
comments.author: jimngu

comments.text: Either will work fine for these, that is really bounded by the capabilities of your printer. If you have a heated bed then ABS or PLA would work fine. If you do not then definitely stick with PLA as ABS will warp, and that is the last thing that you want for a movement component. PLA is a bit stiffer than ABS, so that is what I used, but use whatever you are more comfortable printing with as that will usually give the best results.

Notes: Printed in 1.75 PLA using my 2mm filament modified Ultimaker2 using a 0.3mm nozzle I used 20% infill but found that if you use long screws to hold on the lid the centre of the screw post can break away. Best to go with 40% at least for the bottom. No reason that a 0.4 mm nozzle and 3.8mm filament would not do as well or better.
The included OpenSCAD source has many comments and is parametric so you next electronic project box could be in here.

Tough enclosure for FG085 Function Generator The scad source file will display 3 different parts to export and make an enclosure suitable for the FG085
The enclosure is in 3 parts controlled by setting the desired part= variable found in the scad source file.
You need to print 1 top, 1 bottom and 4 feet. The print expects you to not use the bottom panel of the FG085 but does try to use the original screws to hold the unit as well as the table saving feet in place in the enclosure. The top is designed to provide some added protection for the little ADJ knob and buttons when carried in your tool kit. Lots of comments and written parametrically, perhaps you can reuse this code for your next electronic project.

The FG085 is very inexpensive and I knew it would be dropped often and live in a kit with a bunch of other things.  I wanted an enclosure that would at least protect the little Adjustment knob and also perhaps have a way to put a lid over the face eventually.  The top is printed right side up on this print to make a well for the buttons to live in.
I also wanted to have access to the USB and Power connectors so by inverting the bottom and putting the screw pillars on the outside it made the walls very close to the device.
The circulation hole grills were designed to print with 45 degree angles which assist in limiting the overhang filament drooping during the print.

description.text:
Hey everybody! Who likes Box and Lid?
Golly, I know I do!
If you do too, here's a Box and Lid for you!
Note: I gave the lid a little wiggle room in the .scad file, so experiment if you want a lid with a tighter fit. The smaller wiggle_room is, the less of it there is. Default wiggle_room = 1, so you might want to set to wiggle_room = 0.75 or something.

I provided several .stl files for ease so you could:
  • Print Box and Lid together
  • Print a BIG Box and BIG Lid separately
  • Print a SMALL Box and SMALL Lid separately
  • Print a HUGE Box and Lid together
  • Print a really boring, lame, euclidean Box and Lid

title: Rail Mounting System for DC Components

description.text:
RMSDC is a rail mounting system for low power DC components like the ones often used with Arduino and RPi projects. Each piece can be joined with small (~3mm) zip ties to quickly assemble a functional hardware interface for a project. Each part is designed to be printed on printers with small build volumes, thus larger pieces are split into multiple parts that can be joined using the "Joiner" pieces.
Each hole is ~3mm in diameter, with the holes center point being 4mm from any edge, and 8mm from the next holes center point. 
Each side rail can be joined to another side rail if it is flipped and overlapped. This way you can expand the system to be as large as you want (within reason). When attaching the angle brackets, use a 2x2 joiner to fill in the gap on the rear of the side rail, this will make the assembled unit much stronger.
The LED Holder part is designed to accept a 5mm Plastic Bevel LED Holder like the ones from Adafruit.

description.text: Get organized! The Manhattan Pegboard Collection for 3D Printers is a group of modern, customizable parts that allow you to generate bins, mounts, holders and even shelves for nearly every object that you may want to have neatly hung on a pegboard. As a NYC native, I never had ‘extra space’ in my home. So when I purchased an Ultimaker 2 3D Printer ten months ago, I knew that I wanted to use it to improve my life. By mounting modular pegboards strategically throughout my home, I have been able to create custom mounts for all of the little things in life and place them exactly where they need to be. I now manage to keep ‘everything in its place’ because everything has a place to go!

• Customizable Holder (2-Peg) for Pegboards
• Customizable Holder (4-Peg) for Pegboards
• Customizable Rounded Holder for Pegboards
• Pedestal Shelf for Pegboards
• USB Cable Holder (6 Cables) for Pegboard You can view all of the custom parts that I have designed for my home here, or you can start printing your own today!

This customizable holder has two pegs centered on the rear and is ideal for being used with small, low weight bearing objects. Additionally, if you eliminate the base of the part (done by modifying the openscad file), you can make mounts such as the hairbrush mount pictured. If you would like to hold items of a larger weight, consider using the Customizable Holder (4-Peg) for Pegboards, which adds a second row of pegs for extra stability.

Notes: Depending on a variety of factors your print results may vary! Some of my prints slide into the pegboard peg holes without issue, and sometimes it requires a bit of extra force. If you find that the pegs are not printing well, make sure your support structures are adequately supporting most or all of the entire peg (depending on your settings).



I print my pegboard pieces using an Ultimaker 2 with an Olsson Block running a 1mm nozzle. The prints in the included photos were printed using Verbatim PLA in White. With this setup I can print durable pegboard parts at a 0.5mm layer height and 2mm walls with reasonable speed.

I made this project for a 4th grade history unit on Ancient Egypt. The students can spell out their names in hieroglyphics in the style of a cartouche. Easiest way to do this is to open the construction kit on Tinkercad.com and then just drag and drop the correct letters into position and delete the extra pieces. This is a very easy project suitable for beginners.
https://tinkercad.com/things/jc2XaoHVt13 Or assemble the parts in you preferred cad program.

• Open the construction kit on Tinkercad.com https://tinkercad.com/things/jc2XaoHVt13
    it may take some time to load.
  • Choose the cartouche shape you want, delete the other one. It may make things easier if you lock the cartouche before moving the hieroglyphics onto it.
  • Drag and drop the hieroglyphics onto the cartouche. Use Edit --> Duplicate if you need extra copies of a symbol. The arrow keys can be helpful in positioning the symbols correctly. You can use Adjust --> Align to center the symbols.
  • Lengthen or shorten the cartouche if necessary
  • Delete all the extra pieces
  • Download your completed model and print
    • If you don't use the Construction Kit on Tinkercad you can import the cartouche and hieroglyphs you want to use into your favorite CAD program and assemble it there. It is more authentic if you inscribe (negative space) the hieroglyphs instead of embossing them (raised positive space).

Objective Students will create a cartouche by spelling out their names in hieroglyphics. Audience This is a 4th grade project that is easy enough for beginners to complete. Preparation This project is intended to be used as part of a lesson on ancient Egypt. Steps
  • Open the construction kit on Tinkercad.com https://tinkercad.com/things/jc2XaoHVt13
    it may take some time to load.
  • Choose the cartouche shape you want, delete the other one. It may make things easier if you lock the cartouche before moving the hieroglyphics onto it.
  • Drag and drop the hieroglyphics onto the cartouche. Use Edit --> Duplicate if you need extra copies of a symbol. The arrow keys can be helpful in positioning the symbols correctly. You can use Adjust --> Align to center the symbols.
  • Lengthen or shorten the cartouche if necessary
  • Delete all the extra pieces
  • Download your completed model and print
    • If you don't use the Construction Kit on Tinkercad you can import the cartouche and hieroglyphs you want to use into your favorite CAD program and assemble it there. It is more authentic if you inscribe (negative space) the hieroglyphs instead of embossing them (raised positive space). Extensions This project simplifies things by assigning a symbol to each letter of the alphabet. The Egyptians used hieroglyphs to represent sounds, so it would be more accurate to spell out a name phonetically. Older or more skilled students can engraved their names on other objects, such as an obelisk. Additional hieroglyphics can be created and included in the project. These can be drawn then converted to SVG format and imported into Tinkercad. Or images of the hieroglyphics can be found on the Internet and converted to SVG format and imported. Results This project hasn't been tested with students yet, but sample models were created and included in here.

title: Sharpie Mount for FirePick Delta Robot

description.text:
Here we have a Sharpie mounting kit for your FirePick Delta robot! 
We are currently using our own FirePick Delta as a development platform to test some ideas, and we wanted to draw things on our work platform. These are the two parts needed to mount a Sharpie branded marker pen to the FirePick's end effector.
A Sharpie pen has a slight taper to it and will taper lock into the 'Sharpe Mount' part, but if you want to use a different pen I've added a couple of through holes that can be tapped M6 if you need to add some grub screws for extra grip.

Printer Brand:

Up!

Printer:

Up Plus2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25 or smaller.

Infill:

Fairly dense

Notes: This was designed to print on the UP! Plus 2 3d printer with no support
) I set the support angle to 10 degrees to achieve this). I usually use a raft but there is no reason that you couldn't print it raftless. Because of the thread, it is best to print this with as fine a resolution as your machine will allow. I printed this at 0.15mm layer height and it feels really good.

The sharpie slides in from the bottom (the threaded end of the mount body). A sharp tap on a hard surface will set it rigidly in place.
If you are using a different brand of pen you might need a bit more grip. Run a 5mm drill through the cross bore hole, and then tap to M6x1.0. You can then add a grub screw to get a bit of extra cursh on the pen.

This model was created in SolidWorks 2007. The thread has a pitch of 2mm, 60 degree tooth form, and 0.4mm crest and root radii.
The female thread inside the nut is designed with 0.5mm clearence from the male part. i.e. both the major and minor diameters of the female thread are 0.5mm greater than that of the male part.
